rComments: Some does the first lecture and after that it's all guest lecturers. CO-OP lectures are important to prepare you but web technologies lectures can be skipped if you know how to code HTML/CSS/JS or can learn on your own. Guest lecturers are great, especially Casey Li, and assignments are easy A's, just hand them in.
Some does not respond to emails at all, the course is mainly taught by a guest professor. Overall he is a mediocre professor, but the course is easy if you work for it.
Not recommended.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Prof is nice and helpful, course is HEFTY. Weekly labs are near impossible and take forever to finish, the group project is the single worst experience of my life. Extremely extensive design project that lasts the entire semester, incredibly stressful. Material is easy enough but constant quizzes are annoying. Can't imagine doing this course irl...

Didn't feel like he was present at all. His lectures were reused recordings from last year (not that it matters, he just read from a script) No discussion about real-world application of soft. arch or any substantial examples. Just dry delivery on terrible slides. Labs were DIY with 0 help from TAs. What a waste of time.
Fine for the most part but the labs are frustrating. You get thrown in blind into technologies with short limited time to complete them. We also don't get solutions to the labs.

Practical course elements involve throwing students blind into learning technologies that are too niche (not industry standard). Professor's delivery of the material is unbelievably dry. Not enough done to link theory to practical examples - it's hard to see how what we'll learn in this course will apply to anything. Skip if you can.

His slides don't make any sense at all, and all of his pre-recorded lectures are just him reading a textbook. Professor, if you're reading this, please word on your slides because they are SOOOOOOOOOOO disorganized. Never taking any of your classes again

Is he even a professor? He barely ever talked during the course and brought a guest to teach the course throughout the semester. I'm not sure why he was even there or was paid at all. While he was nice and informed, I really didn't understand what purpose he served. He is an easy marker but if you lose marks don't expect to be told why.

Since it was online there was no midterm, but there were weekly quizzes that are open book. The questions were very specific some times but most of the answers could be found in his slides. The group project was alot of work and stressful so choose your group wisely. The final was just like the quizzes just longer (40 questions with a 2hour limit)

I dropped this class because we never knew when classes would be happening and after the first month we still hadn't received labwork (he gave it pre-completed for some reason). Didn't want to waste my time with this as a 6th class.

I have troubles sleeping at night knowing that I paid more than 1200$ to take this course He gives 0 examples of whatever graphs he draws about software architecture, threw 4 programming languages at us and ask us to figure out everything alone. i can do that free at home on my own. quizes, assignment, project, midterm and final. Who needs a life

Inconsistent class times, never knew if there was a class on a day. Labs were handed out seemingly already completed, so we didn't get to practice what we learned. Very poor communication in general from this prof which made it impossible to know what to expect.
I dont think he has ever replied to an email and ive had him for 3 courses. The lectures are so monotone, his lectures are like 10 times more powerful than ambien (sleeping drug).

If you reach out to him he's helpful, but otherwise? Lectures are long, sleep inducing. Slide decks have a lot of information and a lot seem pointless - his practice exams aren't long and most of the questions are long answers,but when you arrive to the exam 90% of the multiple choices are based on really random stuff from his slides. Difficult.

I still don't know what I learned from this class. The professor doesn't use a mic, and he doesn't explain concepts properly. His slide decks are too long without any useful information, and he draws random stuff on the board sometimes but fails to get the message across to the class.

Really harsh marker and doesn't explain what is going to be on examinations. He will have multiple choice worth the same as long answer. He will give you a practice exam with alot of long answer then not even use that information at all. He will pull multiple choice questions from the bottom of slides that everyone just skims over.
obscure prof. Labs doable. marking harsh. lectures pointless ie boring
Don't take this course at all. Lots of assignments, his way for marking is very bad.
Not an easy course. expect a lot of reading, assignments and hard exams.

He teaches like 10 tools in a matter of 3 months and expects expertise in all of them. Too much assignments, hard research papers to read and the final paper is too tough. Not an easy course to do. Avoid if possible.
If you have questions, don't hesitate to ask. He's willing to move assignments if you are having troubles meeting deadlines (but not for laziness). Ask for a cheat sheet on the final.
just an issue, lectures talk about how to add numbers, assignments ask about doing integrals, exams ask about how to solve EMC^2.
Assignments in this class were BRUTALL!!!!! the prof is fairly clear and he is an easy marker which is good. He is over all a decent professor.

The course material is not difficult and he isnt the most stimulating professor but does an alright job of getting you to understand what may seem tricky. Assignments are long but easy, and the Midterm and Final use alot of what is learnt in the lectures and assignments.
Stephane Some is very helpful towards students and tries his best.
